[2] Indonesia (Riau)
Date: Fri 28 Nov 2008
Source: Batam Pos [in Indonesian, machine trans., edited]
<http://batampos.co.id/kepri/kepri/dbd_sudah_klb/>


The cases of dengue fever in the Tanjung Pinang City, Kepulauan Riau
province, have become an outbreak because during November 2008 as
many as 67 [dengue] illness sufferers have been recorded. The head of
the Health Section of Tanjung Pinang City, Eka Hanasarianto, said
this is the 1st time that dengue cases in Tanjung Pinang City have
reached the outbreak category.

"In the previous month there were only 27 cases, now the increase is
twice that," he said. He said a 3-year-old child died as a result of
being attacked by dengue virus.'' This year [2008] there have been 5
dengue fever sufferers who died," he said. Eka suggested during
January-November 2008 as many as 170 dengue cases have been recorded
in Tanjung Pinang City.

In the past week [week of 16-22 Nov 2008] 2 children died and several
people underwent medical treatment.

The number [of dengue cases] was not yet increased by several
residents who claimed to have had [dengue] fever, because malaria has
not yet been ruled out in these cases.

It was reported that in the case of dengue fever, the official of the
city of Tanjung Pinang, Suryatati A Manan, considered that the
control and eradication [of dengue virus vector mosquitoes] is not easy.

Concern was expressed that continuing the fogging activity could
cause a new problem, that is by causing [insecticide] resistance of
the mosquitoes. At this time the appropriate method to deal with
dengue outbreaks is the application of "3M plus": that is draining
the places of water collection in an orderly fashion at least weekly,
treatment of water catchments with abate powder [a larvicide. -
Mod.TY], covering places of water storage, and burying discarded
things that could collect rain water.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

Tanjung Pinang, Riau province, is located on Bintan Island, which has
over 150 000 population. An interactive map of this area can be accessed at
<http://www.maplandia.com/indonesia/riau/>.
The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Indonesia showing the
