[4] Mexico (Jalisco)
Date: Mon 8 Dec 2008
Source: El Informador [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.informador.com.mx/primera/2008/60946/6/confirman-mas-casos-de-dengue.htm>


More dengue cases are confirmed
-------------------------------
So far this year [2008], the municipalities most affected by [dengue]
virus are Zapopan, Puerto Vallarta, Guadalajara, and Tlaquepaque.

It's a fact. The dengue outbreak in [Jalisco] state has not ended,
even with the lower temperatures, which are not the best environment
for the mosquito that transmits the virus.

The Secretariat of Health of Jalisco confirmed an additional 20
dengue cases in the state, and this time the most affected place is
the El Pitillal area in Puerto Vallarta.

These cases occurred in epidemiological week 49 [1-5 Dec 2008]. With
these latest findings, [the dengue cases] total 629 people who have
been infected by the virus, distributed in 32 municipalities.

A week ago, the Jalisco Director of Public Health, Elizabeth Ulloa
Robles, announced that the [dengue] prevention activities are
continuing and will go on throughout 2009, as a new protection
strategy for the population. It is possible that next year [2009] the
outbreak will be DHF.

[Byline: Thamara Villasenor]
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The cities of Guadalajara and Puerto Vallarta are major tourist
destinations, especially during the high season, which has just
started. Dengue outbreaks are likely to keep tourists away, with
unfortunate economic impacts locally.

A map of Mexico showing the location of the states and Guadalajara,
Jalisco, can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/mexico_pol97.jpg>.
The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Mexico can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed?g=4005539&v=24,-102.5,5>. - Mod.TY]

